</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL NARROW">
<FONT COLOR="#A7A9AB">
<B>
	CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:24PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:18PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<FONT COLOR="#9C9D9D">
	Notes to the Consolidated Financial Statements
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the years ended September&nbsp;30, 2016 and 2015
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	(tabular amounts only are in thousands of Canadian dollars, except per share data)
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL; FONT-SIZE:12PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="7%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
<B>
	3.
</B>
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<B>
	Summary of significant accounting policies (continued)
</B>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	FINANCIAL INSTRUMENTS (CONTINUED)
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	Fair value hierarchy
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Fair value measurements recognized in the
	balance sheet are categorized in accordance with the following levels:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:3%; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Level 1: quoted prices (unadjusted) in active markets for
	identical assets or liabilities;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:3%; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Level 2: inputs other than quoted prices included in Level 1, but that are observable for the asset
	or liability, either directly or indirectly; and
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:3%; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Level 3: inputs for the asset or liability that are not based on observable market
	data.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	DERIVATIVE FINANCIAL INSTRUMENTS AND HEDGING TRANSACTIONS
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The Company enters into a variety of derivative financial instruments to manage its exposure to interest rate and foreign currency exchange risks. No
	derivative financial instruments are held or used for trading purposes.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Derivative financial instruments are initially recognized at fair value at
	the date the derivative contracts are entered into and are subsequently remeasured to their fair value at the end of each reporting date. The resulting gain or loss is recognized in the consolidated statements of earnings unless the derivative is
	designated and is effective as a hedging instrument, in which event the timing of the recognition in the consolidated statements of earnings depends on the nature of the hedge relationship. At the inception of a hedge relationship, the Company
	formally designates and documents the hedge relationship to which the Company wishes to apply hedge accounting and the risk management objective and strategy for undertaking the hedge. The documentation includes identification of the hedging
	instrument, the hedged item or transaction, the nature of the risk being hedged and how the Company will assess the effectiveness of changes in the hedging instrument&#146;s fair value in offsetting the exposure to changes in the hedged item&#146;s
	fair value or cash flows attributable to the hedged risk. Such hedges are expected to be highly effective in achieving offsetting changes in fair value or cash flows and are assessed on an ongoing basis to determine that they actually have been
	highly effective throughout the financial reporting periods for which they were designated.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The cash flows of the hedging transactions are classified
	in the same manner as the cash flows of the position being hedged. Derivative financial instruments used as hedging items are recorded at fair value in the consolidated balance sheets under current derivative financial instruments, long-term
	financial assets or long-term derivative financial instruments. Valuation models, such as discounted cash flow analysis using observable market inputs, are utilized to determine the fair values of the derivative financial instruments.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	NET INVESTMENT HEDGES
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	Hedges on net investments in foreign operations
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The Company uses cross-currency swaps and foreign currency denominated long-term debt to hedge portions of the Company&#146;s net investments in
	its U.S. and European operations. Foreign exchange translation gains or losses on the net investments and the effective portions of gains or losses on instruments hedging the net investments are recorded in other comprehensive income. To the extent
	that the hedge is ineffective, such differences are recognized in consolidated statements of earnings. When the hedged net investment is disposed of, the relevant amount in other comprehensive income is transferred to earnings as part of the gain or
	loss on disposal.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	CASH FLOW HEDGES
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	Cash flow hedges on future revenue
	and long-term debt
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The majority of the Company&#146;s costs are denominated in currency other than the Canadian dollar. The risk of foreign
	exchange fluctuation impacting the results is substantially mitigated by matching the Company&#146;s costs with revenue denominated in the same currency. In certain cases where there is a substantial imbalance for a specific currency, the Company
	enters into foreign currency forward contracts to hedge the variability in the foreign currency exchange rates.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The Company also uses interest rate
	and cross currency swaps to hedge either the cash flow exposure or the foreign exchange exposure of the long-term debt.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:18PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL NARROW">
<FONT COLOR="#AAACAC">
	72
</FONT>
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage134"></A>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL NARROW" ALIGN="RIGHT">
<FONT COLOR="#A7A9AB">
<B>
	FISCAL 2016
</B>
	RESULTS
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:24PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:18PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<FONT COLOR="#9C9D9D">
	Notes to the Consolidated Financial Statements
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the years ended September&nbsp;30, 2016 and 2015
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	(tabular amounts only are in thousands of Canadian dollars, except per share data)
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL; FONT-SIZE:12PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="7%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
<B>
	3.
</B>
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<B>
	Summary of significant accounting policies (continued)
</B>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	DERIVATIVE FINANCIAL INSTRUMENTS AND HEDGING TRANSACTIONS (CONTINUED)
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	CASH FLOW HEDGES (CONTINUED)
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Those derivatives are documented as cash flow hedges and no component of the derivative contracts&#146; fair value are excluded from the assessment and
	measurement of hedge effectiveness. The effective portion of the change in fair value of the derivative financial instruments is recognized in other comprehensive income and the ineffective portion, if any, in the consolidated statements of
	earnings. The effective portion of the change in fair value of the derivatives is reclassified out of other comprehensive income into the consolidated statements of earnings when the hedged element is recognized in the consolidated statements of
	earnings.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	FAIR VALUE HEDGES
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	Fair value hedges on Senior U.S. unsecured
	notes
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The Company entered into interest rate swaps to hedge the fair value exposure of the issued fixed rate Senior U.S. unsecured notes. Under
	the interest rate swaps, the Company receives a fixed rate of interest and pays interest at a variable rate on the notional amount.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The changes in
	the fair value of the interest rate swaps are recognized in the consolidated statements of earnings as finance costs. The changes in the fair value of the hedged items attributable to the risk hedged is recorded as part of the carrying value of the
	Senior U.S. unsecured notes and are also recognized in the consolidated statements of earnings as finance costs. If the hedged items are derecognized, the unamortized fair value is recognized immediately in the consolidated statements of earnings.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	EMPLOYEE BENEFITS
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The Company operates post-employment
	benefit plans of both a defined contribution and defined benefit nature.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The cost of defined contribution plans is charged to the consolidated
	statements of earnings on the basis of contributions payable by the Company during the year.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For defined benefits plans, the defined benefit
	obligations are calculated by independent actuaries using the projected unit credit method. The retirement benefits obligations in the consolidated balance sheets represent the present value of the defined benefit obligation as reduced by the fair
	value of plan assets. The retirement benefits assets are recognized to the extent that the Company can benefit from refunds or a reduction in future contributions. Retirement benefit plans that are funded by the payment of insurance premiums are
	treated as defined contribution plans unless the Company has an obligation either to pay the benefits directly when they fall due or to pay further amounts if assets accumulated with the insurer do not cover all future employee benefits. In such
	circumstances, the plan is treated as a defined benefit plan.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Insurance policies are treated as plan assets of a defined benefit plan if the proceeds
	of the policy:
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL; FONT-SIZE:9PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	-
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY" STYLE=" MARGIN-TOP:0PT ; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL; FONT-SIZE:9PT">
	Can only be used to fund employee benefits;
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL; FONT-SIZE:9PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	-
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY" STYLE=" MARGIN-TOP:0PT ; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL; FONT-SIZE:9PT">
	Are not available to the Company&#146;s creditors; and
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL; FONT-SIZE:9PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	-
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY" STYLE=" MARGIN-TOP:0PT ; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL; FONT-SIZE:9PT">
	Either cannot be paid to the Company unless the proceeds represent surplus assets not needed to meet all the benefit
	obligations or are a reimbursement for benefits already paid by the Company.
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Insurance policies that do not meet the above criteria
	are treated as non-current investments and are held at fair value as long-term financial assets in the consolidated balance sheets.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The actuarial
	valuations used to determine the cost of defined benefit pension plans and their present value involve making assumptions about discount rates, future salary and pension increases, inflation rates and mortality. Any changes in these assumptions will
	impact the carrying amount of pension obligations. In determining the appropriate discount rate management considers the interest rates of high quality corporate bonds that are denominated in the currency in which the benefits will be paid, and that
	have terms to maturity approximating the terms of the related pension liability.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:18PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL NARROW" ALIGN="RIGHT">
<FONT COLOR="#AAACAC">
	73
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL NARROW">
<FONT COLOR="#A7A9AB">
<B>
	CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:24PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:18PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<FONT COLOR="#9C9D9D">
	Notes to the Consolidated Financial Statements
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the years ended September&nbsp;30, 2016 and 2015
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	(tabular amounts only are in thousands of Canadian dollars, except per share data)
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL; FONT-SIZE:12PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="7%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
<B>
	3.
</B>
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<B>
	Summary of significant accounting policies (continued)
</B>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	EMPLOYEE BENEFITS (CONTINUED)
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The current service cost is recognized in the consolidated statements of earnings under costs of services, selling and administrative. The net interest
	cost calculated by applying the discount rate to the net defined benefit liability or asset is recognized as net finance cost or income. When the benefits of a plan are changed or when a plan is curtailed, the resulting change in benefit that
	relates to past service or the gain or loss on curtailment is recognized immediately in the consolidated statements of earnings. The gains or losses on the settlement of a defined benefit plan are recognized when the settlement occurs.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Remeasurements on defined benefit plans include actuarial gains and losses, changes in the effect of the asset ceiling and the return on plan assets,
	excluding the amount included in net interest on the net defined liability or assets. Remeasurements are charged or credited to other comprehensive income in the period in which they arise.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	FUTURE ACCOUNTING STANDARD CHANGES
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The following standards
	have been issued but are not yet effective:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	IFRS 15 - Revenue from Contracts with Customers
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	In May 2014, the IASB issued IFRS 15, &#147;Revenue from Contracts with Customers&#148;, to specify how and when to recognize revenue as well as requiring
	the provision of more informative and relevant disclosures. The standard supersedes IAS 18, &#147;Revenue&#148;, IAS 11, &#147;Construction Contracts&#148;, and other revenue related interpretations. The standard will be effective on October&nbsp;1,
	2018 for the Company, with earlier adoption permitted. The Company is currently evaluating the impact of this standard on its consolidated financial statements.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	IFRS 9 - Financial Instruments
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	In July 2014, the IASB amended
	IFRS 9, &#147;Financial Instruments&#148;, to bring together the classification and measurement, impairment and hedge accounting phases of the IASB&#146;s project to replace IAS 39, &#147;Financial Instruments: Recognition and Measurement&#148;. The
	standard supersedes all previous versions of IFRS 9 and will be effective on October&nbsp;1, 2018 for the Company with earlier adoption permitted. The Company is currently evaluating the impact of this standard on its consolidated financial
	statements.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	IFRS 16 - Leases
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	In January 2016, the IASB
	issued IFRS 16, &#147;Leases&#148;, to set out the principles for the recognition, measurement, presentation and disclosure of leases for both parties to a lease contract. The standard supersedes IAS 17, &#147;Leases&#148;, &#147;Leases&#148;, and
	other lease related Interpretations. The standard will be effective on October&nbsp;1, 2019 for the Company with earlier adoption permitted only if IFRS 15 &#147;Revenue from Contracts with Customers&#148; is also applied. The Company is currently
	evaluating the impact of this standard on its consolidated financial statements.
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:16PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>

	For the years ended September 30, 2016 and 2015

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The Company&#146;s
	operations are managed through the following seven operating segments referred to as our Strategic Business Units, namely: United States of America (&#147;U.S.&#148;); Nordics; Canada; France (including Luxembourg and Morocco) (&#147;France&#148;);
	United Kingdom (&#147;U.K.&#148;); Eastern, Central and Southern Europe (primarily Netherlands and Germany) (&#147;ECS&#148;); and Asia Pacific (including Australia, India and the Philippines) (&#147;Asia Pacific&#148;). The operating segments
	reflect the current management structure and the way that the chief operating decision-maker, who is the President and Chief Executive Officer of the Company, evaluates the business.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The Company completed the annual impairment test as at September&nbsp;30, 2016 and did not identify any impairment.
</P>

<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	1
</SUP>
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY" STYLE=" MARGIN-TOP:0PT ; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL; FONT-SIZE:7PT">
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
</SUP>
	As at September&nbsp;30, 2016, the timing of cash outflows relating
	to these provisions ranges between one and seven years (one and eight years as at September&nbsp;30, 2015) and they were discounted at a weighted average rate of 0.77% (0.85% as at September&nbsp;30, 2015). The reversals of unused amounts are mostly
	due to favourable settlements.
</P>
</TD>

	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL; FONT-SIZE:7PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	2
</SUP>
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY" STYLE=" MARGIN-TOP:0PT ; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL; FONT-SIZE:7PT">
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
</SUP>
	As at September&nbsp;30, 2016, litigation and claims include
	provisions related to tax exposure (other than those related to income tax), contractual disputes, employee claims and other of nil, $5,289,000 and $3,711,000, respectively (as at September&nbsp;30, 2015, $9,854,000, $6,405,000 and $7,900,000,
	respectively). The reversals of unused amounts are mostly due to favourable settlements of tax exposures and employee claims.
</P>
</TD>

</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:3PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL; FONT-SIZE:7PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	3
</SUP>
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY" STYLE=" MARGIN-TOP:0PT ; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL; FONT-SIZE:7PT">
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
</SUP>
	As at September&nbsp;30, 2016, the decommissioning liability was
	based on the expected cash flows of $37,472,000 ($39,574,000 as at September&nbsp;30, 2015) and was discounted at a weighted average rate of 0.98% (1.13% as at September&nbsp;30, 2015). The timing of the settlement of these obligations ranges
	between one and eleven years as at September&nbsp;30, 2016 (one and eight years as at September&nbsp;30, 2015). The reversals of unused amounts are mostly due to favourable settlements.
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:3PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL; FONT-SIZE:7PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	4
</SUP>
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY" STYLE=" MARGIN-TOP:0PT ; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL; FONT-SIZE:7PT">
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
</SUP>
	During the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2015, the Company announced
	a restructuring program of approximately $60,000,000 to advance the realization of benefits associated with productivity enablers and other cost initiatives expected to yield savings throughout fiscal 2016. For the year ended September&nbsp;30,
	2016, the Company incurred $29,100,000 of the announced program ($35,903,000 during the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2015) of which $29,100,000 ($32,836,000 for the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2015) was accounted for in the provision for
	restructuring and nil ($3,067,000 for the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2015) was accounted for in the provision for onerous leases.
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:3PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:1%; FONT-SIZE:7PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	During the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2016, the Company paid in total $57,353,000 related to the restructuring program ($1,567,000
	during the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2015) of which $55,568,000 ($1,567,000 for the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2015) was for restructuring and $1,785,000 (nil for the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2015) was for onerous leases. In addition,
	during the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2016, the Company paid in total $19,431,000 related to the integration of Logica plc ($74,363,000 during the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2015) of which $14,156,000 ($68,849,000 for the year ended
	September&nbsp;30, 2015) was for restructuring and $5,275,000 ($5,514,000 for the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2015) was for onerous leases.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:1%; FONT-SIZE:7PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The Company has an unsecured committed revolving credit facility available for an amount of $1,500,000,000
	that expires in December 2019. This facility bears interest at Bankers&#146; acceptance, LIBOR or Canadian prime, plus a variable margin that is determined based on the Company&#146;s leverage ratio. As at September&nbsp;30, 2016, no amount was
	drawn upon this facility. Also, an amount of $33,914,000 has been committed against this facility to cover various letters of credit issued for clients and other parties. On November&nbsp;8, 2016, the facility was extended by two years to December
	2021 and can be further extended. There were no material changes in the terms and conditions including interest rates and banking covenants. The unsecured committed revolving credit facility contains covenants that require the Company to maintain
	certain financial ratios (Note 31). As at September&nbsp;30, 2016, the Company was in compliance with these covenants.
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:3PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL; FONT-SIZE:7PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	1
</SUP>
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY" STYLE=" MARGIN-TOP:0PT ; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL; FONT-SIZE:7PT">
	As at September&nbsp;30, 2016, an amount of $623,248,000 was drawn, plus fair value adjustments relating to interest rate
	swaps designated as fair value hedges of $7,992,000 less financing fees of $359,000. The private placement financing with U.S. institutional investors is comprised of three tranches of Senior U.S. unsecured notes, with a weighted average maturity of
	3.4 years and a weighted average interest rate of 4.57% (4.57% in 2015). The Senior U.S. unsecured notes contain covenants that require the Company to maintain certain financial ratios (Note 31). As at September&nbsp;30, 2016, the Company was in
	compliance with these covenants.
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

	&nbsp;

<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
</SUP>
	As at September&nbsp;30, 2016, an amount of $1,102,865,000 was
	drawn, less financing fees of $710,000. The private placement is comprised of four tranches of Senior U.S. unsecured notes and one tranche of Senior euro unsecured note, with a weighted average maturity of 5.9 years and a weighted average interest
	rate of 3.62% (3.62% in 2015). The Senior unsecured notes contain covenants that require the Company to maintain certain financial ratios (Note 31). As at September&nbsp;30, 2016, the Company was in compliance with these covenants.
</P>

<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY" STYLE=" MARGIN-TOP:0PT ; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL; FONT-SIZE:7PT">
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
</SUP>
	In January 2016, the Company repaid in advance, without penalty, the
	remaining portion of the May 2016 maturing tranche of unsecured committed term loan credit facility for a total amount of $129,736,000. Following the debt repayment, the Company settled the related
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	floating-to-fixed
</FONT>
</FONT>
	interest rate swap with a notional amount of $109,730,000 with no material impact, and settled the related cross-currency swap with a notional amount of $109,730,000 (Note 30).

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL NARROW">
<FONT COLOR="#A7A9AB">
<B>
	CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS
</B>

<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D228504D40F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL NARROW" ALIGN="RIGHT">
<FONT COLOR="#A7A9AB">
<B>
	FISCAL 2016
</B>
	RESULTS
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:24PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:18PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<FONT COLOR="#9C9D9D">
	Notes to the Consolidated Financial Statements
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the years ended September 30, 2016 and 2015
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	(tabular amounts only are in thousands of Canadian dollars, except per share data)
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:24PT; MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL; FONT-SIZE:12PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="7%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
<B>
	15.
</B>
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<B>
	Income taxes (continued)
</B>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	As
	at September&nbsp;30, 2016, the Company had $744,092,000 ($1,104,894,000 as at September&nbsp;30, 2015) in operating tax losses carried forward, of which $105,505,000 ($131,980,000 as at September&nbsp;30, 2015) expire at various dates up to 2036
	and $638,587,000 ($972,914,000 as at September&nbsp;30, 2015) have no expiry dates. The Company recognized a deferred tax asset of $170,075,000 ($267,350,000 as at September&nbsp;30, 2015) on the losses carried forward and recognized a valuation
	allowance of $39,430,000 ($48,653,000 as at September&nbsp;30, 2015). The resulting net deferred tax asset of $130,645,000 ($218,697,000 as at September&nbsp;30, 2015) is the amount that is more likely than not to be realized, based on deferred tax
	liabilities reversal and future taxable profits. The unrecognized losses amounted to $143,700,000 ($167,100,000 as at September&nbsp;30, 2015).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	As at
	September&nbsp;30, 2016, the Company had $662,334,000 ($663,275,000 as at September&nbsp;30, 2015) in
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	non-operating
</FONT>
	tax losses carried forward that have no expiry dates. The Company recognized a deferred tax
	asset of $113,125,000 ($130,903,000 as at September&nbsp;30, 2015) on the losses carried forward and recognized a valuation allowance of $109,045,000 ($125,203,000 as at September&nbsp;30, 2015). The resulting net deferred tax asset of $4,080,000
	($5,700,000 as at September&nbsp;30, 2015) is the amount that is more likely than not to be realized, based on deferred tax liabilities reversal and future taxable profits. The unrecognized losses amounted to $638,300,000 ($634,800,000 as at
	September&nbsp;30, 2015).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	As at September&nbsp;30, 2016, the Company has not recorded deferred tax liabilities on undistributed earnings of its
	foreign subsidiaries when they are considered indefinitely reinvested, unless it is probable that these temporary differences will reverse. Upon distribution of these earnings in the form of dividends or otherwise, the Company may be subject to
	taxes. The temporary differences associated with investments in foreign subsidiaries for which a deferred tax liability has not been recognized amounted to $2,339,815,000 ($2,031,729,000 as at September&nbsp;30, 2015).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The cash and cash equivalents held by foreign subsidiaries were $557,800,000 as at September&nbsp;30, 2016 ($263,607,000 as at September&nbsp;30, 2015).
	The tax implications and impact related to its repatriation have been accounted for and will not materially affect the Company&#146;s liquidity.
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:18PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL; FONT-SIZE:12PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="7%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
<B>
	16.
</B>
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<B>
	Employee benefits
</B>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The Company operates various post-employment plans, including defined benefit
	and defined contribution pension plans as well as other benefit plans for its employees.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	DEFINED BENEFIT PLANS
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The Company operates defined benefit pension plans primarily for the benefit of employees in U.K., Germany, France, with smaller plans in other countries.
	The benefits are based on pensionable salary and years of service. U.K. and Germany plans are funded with the assets held in separate funds. The plan in France is unfunded.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The defined benefit plans expose the Company to interest risk, inflation risk, longevity risk, currency risk and market investment risk.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:18PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL NARROW" ALIGN="RIGHT">
<FONT COLOR="#A7A9AB">
	85
</FONT>
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage147"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D228504D40F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL NARROW">
<FONT COLOR="#A7A9AB">
<B>
	CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:24PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:18PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<FONT COLOR="#9C9D9D">
	Notes to the Consolidated Financial Statements
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the years ended September 30, 2016 and 2015
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	(tabular amounts only are in thousands of Canadian dollars, except per share data)
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:24PT; MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL; FONT-SIZE:12PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="7%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
<B>
	16.
</B>
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<B>
	Employee benefits (continued)
</B>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	DEFINED
	BENEFIT PLANS (CONTINUED)
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The following description focuses mainly on
	plans registered in U.K., Germany and France:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	U.K.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	In
	U.K., the Company has three defined benefit pension plans, CMG U.K. Pension Scheme, Logica U.K. Pension&nbsp;&amp; Life Assurance Scheme and Logica Defined Benefit Pension Plan.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The CMG U.K. Pension Scheme is closed to new members and is closed to further accrual of rights for existing members. The Logica U.K. Pension&nbsp;&amp;
	Life Assurance Scheme is still open but only for employees who come from the civil service with protected pensions. Logica Defined Benefit Pension Plan was created to mirror the Electricity Industry pension scheme and was created for employees that
	worked for National Grid and Welsh Water with protected benefits.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Both the Logica U.K. Pension&nbsp;&amp; Life Assurance Scheme and Logica Defined
	Benefit Pension Plan are employer and employee based contribution plans.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The trustees are the custodians of the defined benefit pension plans and are
	responsible for the plan administration, including investment strategies. The trustees review periodically the investment and the asset allocation policies. As such, CMG U.K. Pension Scheme policy is to target an allocation of 35% to return-seeking
	assets such as equities and 65% towards a mixture of assets such as bonds and liability-driven investments such as investment funds; Logica Defined Benefit Pension plan policy is to invest 30% of the plan&#146;s assets in equities and 70% in bonds;
	Logica U.K. Pension&nbsp;&amp; Life Assurance Scheme target is to invest 20% of the Scheme&#146;s assets in equities and 80% in bonds.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	U.K. Pensions
	Act 2004 requires that full formal actuarial valuations are carried out at least every three years to determine the contributions that the Company should pay in order for the plan to meet its statutory objective, taking into account the assets
	already held. In the interim years, the trustees need to obtain estimated funding updates unless the scheme has less than 100 members in total.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The
	latest funding actuarial valuations of the CMG U.K. Pension Scheme as well as the Logica U.K. Pension&nbsp;&amp; Life Assurance Scheme was performed in September 2015 and the results are expected to be available by the end of the 2016 calendar year.
	In the meantime, the Company continues to contribute to the CMG U.K. Pension Scheme in line with the last funding actuarial valuation, the quarterly payments of $3,074,000 to cover the deficit and approximately $342,000 to cover administration
	expenses.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The latest funding actuarial valuation for the Logica Defined Benefit Pension Plan was performed in June 2014 and reported a deficit of
	$3,074,000. During the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2016, the Company contributed monthly payments of $102,000 to eliminate the funding shortfall and $10,000 to cover administration expenses.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	Germany
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	In Germany, the Company has numerous defined benefit
	pension plans which are all closed to new members. In the majority of the plans, upon retirement of employees, the benefits are in the form of a monthly pension and in a few plans, the employees will receive an indemnity in the form of a
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	lump-sum
</FONT>
	payment. About one third of the plans are bound by the former works council agreements. There are no mandatory funding requirements. The plans are funded by the contributions made by the Company. In some
	plans, insurance policies are taken out to fund retirement benefit plans. These do not qualify as plan assets and are presented as reimbursement rights.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	France
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	In France, the retirement indemnities are provided in accordance with the Labour Code. Upon retirement, employees will receive an indemnity
	(depending on the salary and seniority in the Company) in the form of a
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	lump-sum
</FONT>
	payment.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:18PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL NARROW">
<FONT COLOR="#A7A9AB">
	86
</FONT>
</P>

<EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<A NAME="FIS_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE_97"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Assumptions regarding future mortality are set based on actuarial advice in
	accordance with published statistics and experience in each country. Mortality assumptions for the most significant countries are based on the following post-retirement mortality tables for the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2016: (1) U.K.: 100%
	S2PxA (year of birth) plus CMI_2015 projections with 1.25% p.a. minimum long term improvement rate, (2)&nbsp;Germany: Heubeck RT2005G (3)&nbsp;and France: INSEE TVTD 2009-2011.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL NARROW" ALIGN="RIGHT">
<FONT COLOR="#A7A9AB">
<B>
	FISCAL 2016
</B>
	RESULTS

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:24PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:18PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<FONT COLOR="#9C9D9D">
	Notes to the Consolidated Financial Statements
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the years ended September 30, 2016 and 2015
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	(tabular amounts only are in thousands of Canadian dollars, except per share data)
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:24PT; MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL; FONT-SIZE:12PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="7%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
<B>
	16.
</B>
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<B>
	Employee benefits (continued)
</B>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	DEFINED
	BENEFIT PLANS (CONTINUED)
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The Company expects to contribute $19,161,000 to
	defined benefit plans during the next year, of which $16,046,000 relates to the U.K. plans, and $3,115,000 relating to the other plans. The contributions will include new benefit accruals and deficit recovery payments.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	DEFINED CONTRIBUTION PLANS
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The Company also operates defined
	contribution retirement plans. In some countries, contributions are made into state pension plans. The pension cost for defined contribution plans amounted to $236,678,000 in 2016 ($228,746,000 in 2015).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	In addition, in Sweden the Company contributes to a multi-employer plan, Alecta SE (&#147;Alecta&#148;) pension plan, which is a defined benefit pension
	plan. This pension plan is classified as a defined contribution plan as sufficient information is not available to use defined benefit accounting. Alecta lacks the possibility of establishing an exact distribution of assets and provisions to the
	respective employers. The Company&#146;s proportion of the total contributions to the plan is 0.77% and the Company&#146;s proportion of the total number of active members in the plan is 0.56%.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Alecta uses a collective funding ratio to determine the surplus or deficit in the pension plan. Any surplus or deficit in the plan will affect the amount
	of future contributions payable. The collective funding is the difference between Alecta&#146;s assets and the commitments to the policy holders and insured individuals. The collective solvency is normally allowed to vary between 125% and 155%, with
	the target being 140%. At September&nbsp;30, 2016, Alecta&#146;s collective funding ratio was 142% (148% in 2015). The plan expense was $34,528,000 in 2016 ($38,052,000 in 2015). The Company expects to contribute $30,028,000 to the plan during the
	next year.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	OTHER BENEFIT PLANS
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The Company maintains
	deferred compensation plans covering some of its U.S. and Germany management. Some of the plans include assets that will be used to fund the liabilities. As at September&nbsp;30, 2016, the deferred compensation liability totaled $43,844,000
	($40,940,000 as at September&nbsp;30, 2015) (Note 14) and the deferred compensation assets totaled $42,139,000 ($38,238,000 as at September&nbsp;30, 2015) (Note 10).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the deferred compensation plan in U.S., a trust was established so that the plan assets could be segregated; however, the assets are subject to the
	Company&#146;s general creditors in the case of bankruptcy. The assets composed of investments vary with employees&#146; contributions and changes in the value of the investments. The change in liabilities associated with the plan is equal to the
	change of the assets. The assets in the trust and the associated liabilities totaled $41,423,000 as at September&nbsp;30, 2016 ($37,439,000 as at September&nbsp;30, 2015).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>

<FONT COLOR="#A7A9AB">
	93
</FONT>
</P>

	For the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2016, $11,834,000 of the net unrealized gains previously recognized in other
	comprehensive income, net of income tax expense of $6,725,000, were reclassified to net earnings for derivative financial instruments designated as cash flow hedges ($9,092,000 of the net unrealized gains net of income tax expense of $4,101,000 for

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:24PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:18PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<FONT COLOR="#9C9D9D">
	Notes to the Consolidated Financial Statements
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the years ended September 30, 2016 and 2015
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	(tabular amounts only are in thousands of Canadian dollars, except per share data)
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:24PT; MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL; FONT-SIZE:12PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="7%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
<B>
	18.
</B>
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<B>
	Capital stock
</B>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Authorized,
	an unlimited number without par value:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	First preferred shares, carrying one vote per share, ranking prior to second preferred shares, Class&nbsp;A
	subordinate shares and Class&nbsp;B shares with respect to the payment of dividends;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Second preferred shares,
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	non-voting,
</FONT>
	ranking prior to Class&nbsp;A subordinate shares and Class&nbsp;B shares with respect to the payment of dividends;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Class&nbsp;A subordinate shares, carrying one vote per share, participating equally with Class&nbsp;B shares with respect to the payment of dividends and
	convertible into Class&nbsp;B shares under certain conditions in the event of certain takeover bids on Class&nbsp;B shares;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Class&nbsp;B shares,
	carrying ten votes per share, participating equally with Class&nbsp;A subordinate shares with respect to the payment of dividends and convertible at any time at the option of the holder into Class&nbsp;A subordinate shares.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For 2016 and 2015, the Class&nbsp;A subordinate and the Class&nbsp;B shares varied as follows:
</P>

	The carrying value of Class&nbsp;A subordinate shares includes $21,972,000 ($13,474,000 in 2015), which corresponds to a
	reduction in contributed surplus representing the value of accumulated compensation costs associated with the stock options exercised during the year.

<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	2
</SUP>
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY" STYLE=" MARGIN-TOP:0PT ; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL; FONT-SIZE:7PT">
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
</SUP>
	During the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2016, 969,241 PSUs were
	exercised (316,857 during the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2015) with a recorded value of $21,250,000 ($8,668,000 as at September&nbsp;30, 2015) that was removed from contributed surplus. As at September&nbsp;30, 2016, 1,192,308 Class&nbsp;A
	subordinate shares were held in trust under the PSU plan (1,719,827 as at September&nbsp;30, 2015) (Note 19b).
</P>

<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">

<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY" STYLE=" MARGIN-TOP:0PT ; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL; FONT-SIZE:7PT">
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
</SUP>
	On January&nbsp;27, 2016, the Company&#146;s Board of Directors
	authorized the renewal of a Normal Course Issuer Bid (&#147;NCIB&#148;) for the purchase of up to 21,425,992 Class&nbsp;A subordinate shares for cancellation on the open market through the TSX. The Class&nbsp;A subordinate shares are available for
	purchase commencing February&nbsp;11, 2016, until no later than February&nbsp;3, 2017, or on such earlier date when the Company completes its purchases or elects to terminate the bid.
</P>

<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY" STYLE=" MARGIN-TOP:0PT ; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL; FONT-SIZE:7PT">
	During the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2016, the Company repurchased 7,112,375 Class&nbsp;A subordinate shares from the
	Caisse de d&eacute;p&ocirc;t et placement du Qu&eacute;bec for a cash consideration of $400,000,000. The excess of the purchase price over the carrying value in the amount of $247,893,000 was charged to retained earnings. In accordance with the
	requirements of TSX, the repurchase is considered in the annual aggregate limit that the Company is entitled to repurchase under its current NCIB. In addition, during the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2016, the Company repurchased 2,207,500
	Class&nbsp;A subordinate shares under the previous NCIB for cash consideration of $117,820,000 and the excess of the purchase price over the carrying value in the amount of $99,553,000 was charged to retained earnings.
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:4PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL; FONT-SIZE:7PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY" STYLE=" MARGIN-TOP:0PT ; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL; FONT-SIZE:7PT">
	During the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2015 the Company repurchased 6,925,735 Class&nbsp;A subordinate shares under the
	previous NCIB for cash consideration of $332,535,000 and the excess of the purchase price over the carrying value in the amount of $275,986,000 was charged to retained earnings. As of September&nbsp;30, 2015, 200,000 of repurchased Class&nbsp;A
	subordinate shares with a carrying value of $1,631,000 and a purchase value of $9,466,000 were held by the Company and were paid and cancelled during the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2016 under the previous NCIB.
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:4PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">

	ended September&nbsp;30, 2016 (288,535 Class&nbsp;A subordinate shares for $11,099,000 during the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2015).

<FONT COLOR="#9C9D9D">
	Notes to the Consolidated Financial Statements
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the years ended September 30, 2016 and 2015
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">

<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL; FONT-SIZE:12PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="7%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
<B>
	19.
</B>
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<B>
	Share-based payments
</B>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL; FONT-SIZE:9PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
<B>
	a)
</B>
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<B>
	Stock options
</B>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Under the Company&#146;s stock option plan, the Board of Directors may grant, at its
	discretion, stock options to purchase Class&nbsp;A subordinate shares to certain employees, officers and directors of the Company and its subsidiaries. The exercise price is established by the Board of Directors and is equal to the closing price of
	the Class&nbsp;A subordinate shares on the TSX on the day preceding the date of the grant. Stock options generally vest over four years from the date of grant conditionally upon achievement of objectives and must be exercised within a
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	ten-year
</FONT>
	period, except in the event of retirement, termination of employment or death. As at September&nbsp;30, 2016, 35,145,143 Class&nbsp;A subordinate shares have been reserved for issuance under the stock
	option plan.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The following table presents information concerning all outstanding stock options granted by the Company:
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">

<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL; FONT-SIZE:7PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>

<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">

</SUP>

</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Expected volatility was determined using statistical formulas and based on the weekly historical average of closing daily share prices over the period of the expected life of stock option.
</TD>

<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL; FONT-SIZE:9PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
<B>
	b)
</B>
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<B>
	Performance share units
</B>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Under the PSU plan, the Board of Directors may grant PSUs to senior
	executives and other key employees (&#147;participants&#148;) which entitle them to receive one Class&nbsp;A subordinate share for each PSU. The vesting performance conditions are determined by the Board of Directors at the time of each grant. PSUs
	expire on the business day preceding December&nbsp;31 of the third calendar year following the end of the fiscal year during which the PSU award was made, except in the event of retirement, termination of employment or death. Granted PSUs vest
	annually over a period of four years from the date of grant conditionally upon achievement of objectives.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Class&nbsp;A subordinate shares purchased
	in connection with the PSU plan are held in trust for the benefit of the participants. The trust, considered as a structured entity, is consolidated in the Company&#146;s consolidated financial statements with the cost of the purchased shares
	recorded as a reduction of capital stock (Note 18).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The following table presents information concerning the number of outstanding PSUs granted by the
	Company:
</P>

<B>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:24PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:18PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<FONT COLOR="#9C9D9D">
	Notes to the Consolidated Financial Statements
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the years ended September 30, 2016 and 2015
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	(tabular amounts only are in thousands of Canadian dollars, except per share data)
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:24PT; MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL; FONT-SIZE:12PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="7%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
<B>
	19.
</B>
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<B>
	Share-based payments (continued)
</B>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL; FONT-SIZE:9PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
<B>
	c)
</B>
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<B>
	Share purchase plan
</B>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Under the share purchase plan, the Company contributes an amount equal to a
	percentage of the employee&#146;s basic contribution, up to a maximum of 3.5%. An employee may make additional contributions in excess of the basic contribution however the Company does not match contributions in the case of such additional
	contributions. The employee and Company contributions are remitted to an independent plan administrator who purchases Class&nbsp;A subordinate shares on the open market on behalf of the employee through either the TSX or New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL; FONT-SIZE:9PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
<B>
	d)
</B>
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<B>
	Deferred share unit plan
</B>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	External members of the Board of Directors (&#147;participants&#148;) are
	entitled to receive part or their entire retainer fee in DSUs. DSUs are granted with immediate vesting and must be exercised no later than December&nbsp;15 of the calendar year immediately following the calendar year during which the participant
	ceases to act as a Director. Each DSU entitles the holder to receive a cash payment equal to the closing price of Class&nbsp;A subordinate shares on the TSX on the payment date. As at September&nbsp;30, 2016, the number of outstanding DSUs was
	107,856 (124,354 DSUs as at September&nbsp;30, 2015).
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL; FONT-SIZE:9PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
<B>
	e)
</B>
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<B>
	Share-based payment costs
</B>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The share-based payment expense recorded in costs of services, selling
	and administrative expenses is as follows:
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>

<FONT COLOR="#9C9D9D">
	Notes to the Consolidated Financial Statements
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the years ended September 30, 2016 and 2015
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	(tabular amounts only are in thousands of Canadian dollars, except per share data)
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:24PT; MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL; FONT-SIZE:12PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="7%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
<B>
	21.
</B>
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<B>
	Construction contracts in progress
</B>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Revenue from systems integration and consulting services under
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	fixed-fee
</FONT>
	arrangements where the outcome of the
	arrangements can be estimated reliably is recognized using the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	percentage-of-completion
</FONT>
</FONT>
	method over the service periods. The Company primarily uses labour costs or
	labour hours to measure the progress towards completion. If the outcome of an arrangement cannot be estimated reliably, revenue is recognized to the extent of arrangement costs incurred that are likely to be recoverable.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Amounts recognized as revenue in excess of billings are classified as work in progress. Amounts received in advance of the delivery of products or
	performances of services are classified as deferred revenue.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The status of the Company&#146;s construction contracts still in progress at the end of
	the reporting period was as follows:

	(&#147;Collaborative Consulting&#148;), a system integration and consulting&nbsp;company headquartered in Boston, Massachusetts. The cash acquisition of all unit holder positions of Collaborative Consulting was completed effective November&nbsp;3,

	Pacific operating segments was $115,367,000, $66,910,000, $69,152,000, $31,933,000, $71,888,000, $42,722,000 and $24,884,000, respectively for the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2015.

	charged to the earnings, during the year was $223,289,000 ($290,713,000 in 2015), net of sublease income of $19,220,000 ($29,256,000 in 2015). As at September&nbsp;30, 2016, the total future minimum sublease payments expected to be received under

	sublease were $25,801,000 ($97,442,000 as at September&nbsp;30, 2015).

<B>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	From time to time, the Company is involved in legal proceedings, audits, claims and
	litigation which primarily relate to tax exposure, contractual disputes and employee claims arising in the ordinary course of its business. Certain of these matters seek damages in significant amounts and will ultimately be resolved when one or more
	future events occur or fail to occur. Although the outcome of such matters is not predictable with assurance, the Company has no reason to believe that the disposition of any such current matter could reasonably be expected to have a materially
	adverse impact on the Company&#146;s financial position, results of operations or the ability to carry on any of its business activities. Claims for which there is a probable unfavourable outcome are recorded in provisions (Note 12).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	In addition, the Company is engaged to provide services under contracts with the U.S. Government. The contracts are subject to extensive legal and
	regulatory requirements and, from time to time, agencies of the U.S. Government investigate whether the Company&#146;s operations are being conducted in accordance with these requirements. Generally, the Government has the right to change the scope
	of, or terminate, these projects at its convenience. The termination or reduction in the scope, of a major government project could have a materially adverse effect on the results of operations and financial condition of the Company.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	Sale of assets and business divestitures
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	In connection with the sale of assets and business divestitures, the Company may be required to pay counterparties for costs and losses incurred as the
	result of breaches in contractual obligations, representations and warranties, intellectual property right infringement and litigation against counterparties, among others. While some of the agreements specify a maximum potential exposure of
	approximately $10,753,000 in total, others do not specify a maximum amount or limited period. It is not possible to reasonably estimate the maximum amount that may have to be paid under such guarantees. The amounts are dependent upon the outcome of
	future contingent events, the nature and likelihood of which cannot be determined at this time. No amount has been accrued in the consolidated balance sheets relating to this type of indemnification as at September&nbsp;30, 2016. The Company does
	not expect to incur any potential payment in connection with these guarantees that could have a materially adverse effect on its consolidated financial statements.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	Other transactions
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	In the normal course of business, the
	Company may provide certain clients, principally governmental entities, with bid and performance bonds. In general, the Company would only be liable for the amount of the bid bonds if the Company refuses to perform the project once the bid is
	awarded. The Company would also be liable for the performance bonds in the event of default in the performance of its obligations. As at September&nbsp;30, 2016, the Company had committed a total of $30,877,000 of these bonds. To the best of its
	knowledge, the Company is in compliance with its performance obligations under all service contracts for which there is a performance or bid bond, and the ultimate liability, if any, incurred in connection with these guarantees would not have a
	materially adverse effect on the Company&#146;s consolidated results of operations or financial condition.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Moreover, the Company has letters of
	credit for a total of $94,983,000 in addition to the letters of credit covered by the unsecured committed revolving credit facility (Note 13). These guarantees are required in some of the Company&#146;s contracts with customers.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	FAIR VALUE MEASUREMENTS
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Fair value is the price that would be received to sell an asset or paid to transfer a liability in an orderly transaction between market participants at
	the measurement date.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">

	hierarchy:

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:18PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<FONT COLOR="#9C9D9D">
	Notes to the Consolidated Financial Statements
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the years ended September 30, 2016 and 2015
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	(tabular amounts only are in thousands of Canadian dollars, except per share data)

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;

<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
