</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2016 revenue was $10,683.3 million, an increase of $396.2 million, or 3.9% over the
	same period of fiscal 2015. On a constant currency basis, revenue increased by 0.2%. Foreign currency rate fluctuations favourably impacted our revenue by $379.4 million or 3.7%. The revenue growth in U.K., France and the increased use of our
	offshore global delivery centers in Asia Pacific compensated for the non-renewal of contracts in the U.S. federal defense market and lower work volumes in the Nordics and ECS segments.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:18PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL NARROW" ALIGN="RIGHT">
<FONT COLOR="#A7A9AB">
	15
</FONT>
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage191"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D228504D40F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
</EFX_MANAGEMENTS_DISCUSSION>
<EFX_MANAGEMENTS_DISCUSSION>
<A NAME="FIS_MANAGEMENTS_DISCUSSION_9"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL NARROW">
<FONT COLOR="#A7A9AB">
<B>
	MANAGEMENT&#146;S DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:24PT; MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	3.4.1. U.S.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2016 revenue in our U.S. segment was $2,878.7 million, an increase of $65.5 million or 2.3% over fiscal 2015. On a
	constant currency basis, revenue decreased by $139.5 million or 5.0%. The change in revenue was mainly driven by the non-renewal of contracts in the U.S. government market, mainly in the defense sector. This was partly offset by an increased volume
	of work within the U.S. federal civilian agencies.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2016, the top two U.S. vertical markets were government and
	financial services, which together accounted for approximately 77% of revenue.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	3.4.2. Nordics
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2016, revenue in our Nordics segment was $1,651.3 million, an increase of $12.3 million or 0.8% over the same period
	of fiscal 2015. On a constant currency basis, revenue decreased by $55.8 million or 3.4%. The change in revenue was mostly due to the expiration of certain infrastructure contracts, lower work volumes, and an increased usage of our offshore delivery
	centers in Asia Pacific. This was partly offset by an increased work volume in Denmark mainly in the MRD vertical market.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the year ended
	September&nbsp;30, 2016, Nordics&#146; top two vertical markets were MRD and government, which together accounted for approximately 65% of revenue.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	3.4.3. Canada
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2016, revenue in our Canada segment was $1,536.3 million, an increase of $2.6 million or 0.2% compared to
	the same period last year. When considering the higher proportion of revenues delivered from our offshore delivery centers in Asia Pacific, our client revenue grew by 2.3%. This increase was mainly due to growth in the financial services market,
	including IP-based services and solutions revenue and new outsourcing contracts within the MRD vertical market. This was partly offset by expiration of certain infrastructure outsourcing contracts and the positive impact on revenue of a client
	arbitration award in Q3 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2016, Canada&#146;s top two vertical markets were financial services and
	telecommunications&nbsp;&amp; utilities, which together accounted for approximately 62% of revenue.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	3.4.4. France
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2016, revenue in our France segment was $1,445.0 million, an increase of $161.6 million or 12.6% over the same
	period of fiscal 2015. On a constant currency basis, revenue increased by $97.6 million or 7.6%. The increase in revenue was mostly due to more work volume across the majority of their vertical markets and, to a lesser extent, to a recent business
	acquisition.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2016, France&#146;s top two vertical markets were MRD and financial services, which together
	accounted for approximately 63% of revenue.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	3.4.5. U.K.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2016, revenue in our U.K. segment was $1,431.7 million, an increase of $100.5 million or 7.5% over fiscal 2015. On a
	constant currency basis, revenue increased by $114.0 million or 8.6%. The increase in revenue was mainly due to new outsourcing contracts in the government market combined with higher work volume in the telecommunication&nbsp;&amp; utilities and
	financial services vertical markets. This was partly offset by lower work volume with a client in the MRD vertical market.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the year ended
	September&nbsp;30, 2016, U.K.&#146;s top two vertical markets were government and telecommunications&nbsp;&amp; utilities, which together accounted for approximately 68% of revenue.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:18PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL NARROW">
<FONT COLOR="#A7A9AB">
	16
</FONT>
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage192"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D228504D40F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL NARROW" ALIGN="RIGHT">
<FONT COLOR="#A7A9AB">
<B>
	FISCAL 2016
</B>
	RESULTS
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:24PT; MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	3.4.6. ECS
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2016, revenue in our ECS segment was $1,198.9 million, a decrease of $12.4 million or 1.0% over fiscal 2015. On a
	constant currency basis, revenue decreased by $59.2 million or 4.9%. The change in revenue was mostly due to lower work volume and projects completed in the Netherlands, lower work volume combined with the divesting of certain low margin contracts
	in Southern Europe and the wind-down of the majority of our operations in South America. This was partly offset by increased work volume in Germany mainly in the MRD and telecommunication&nbsp;&amp; utilities vertical markets.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2016, ECS&#146; top two vertical markets were MRD and telecommunications&nbsp;&amp; utilities, which together
	accounted for approximately 63% of revenue.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	3.4.7. Asia Pacific
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2016, revenue in our Asia Pacific segment was $541.4 million, an increase of $66.0 million or 13.9% over the same
	period of fiscal 2015. On a constant currency basis, revenue increased by $57.7 million or 12.1%. The increase in revenue was due the continued increased demand of our offshore delivery centers across our segments, as our clients continue taking
	advantage of our global delivery network. This was partly offset by lower work volumes in Australia.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2016,
	Asia Pacific&#146;s top two vertical markets were telecommunications&nbsp;&amp; utilities and MRD, which together accounted for approximately 72% of revenue.
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:14PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	3.5.1. Costs of Services, Selling and Administrative
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2016, costs of services, selling and administrative expenses amounted to $9,120.9 million, an increase of $301.9
	million over the same period last year. As a percentage of revenue, cost of services, selling and administrative expenses improved to 85.4% from 85.7%. As a percentage of revenue, our costs of services improved compared to the same period last year
	mainly due to savings related to the recent restructuring program, improved utilization rates and the increased use of our global delivery network. Our selling and administrative expenses, as a percentage of revenue, remained stable.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	During the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2016 the translation of the results of our foreign operations from their local currencies to the Canadian dollar
	unfavourably impacted costs by $325.5 million substantially offsetting the favourable translation impact of $379.4 million on our revenue.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	3.5.2. Foreign
	Exchange Loss
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	During the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2016, CGI incurred $2.0 million of foreign exchange loss, mainly driven by the timing in
	payments combined with the volatility and fluctuation of foreign exchange rates. The Company, in addition to its natural hedges, has a strategy in place to manage its exposure, to the extent possible, to exchange rate fluctuations through the
	effective use of derivatives.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:18PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL NARROW" ALIGN="RIGHT">
<FONT COLOR="#A7A9AB">
	17
</FONT>
</P>

<TD VALIGN="MIDDLE" BGCOLOR="#525252">
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:8PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<FONT COLOR="#FFFFFF">
<B>
	&nbsp;For the years ended September&nbsp;30,
</B>
</FONT>

	&nbsp;

	&nbsp;
</P>

<TD NOWRAP VALIGN="BOTTOM" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1PX SOLID #000000" BGCOLOR="#A9A9A9">

</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2016, adjusted EBIT margin increased to 14.6% from 14.2% for the same period last
	year. The favourable variance in adjusted EBIT margin was primarily due to productivity improvements, the savings driven by our restructuring program and a better mix of profitable revenue.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	3.6.1. U.S.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2016,
	adjusted EBIT in the U.S. segment was $486.3 million, an increase of $32.0 million. Adjusted EBIT margin increased to 16.9% from 16.2% mostly due to additional research and development tax credits and the decrease in amortization of client
	relationships related to the acquisition of Stanley, Inc.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	3.6.2. Nordics
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2016, adjusted EBIT in the Nordics segment was $186.7 million, an increase of $32.9 million, while the adjusted EBIT
	margin improved to 11.3% from 9.4%. The increase in adjusted EBIT margin came mainly from the ongoing cost synergies within our infrastructure business, the improved delivery performance, and the savings generated from the restructuring program.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:18PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL NARROW">
<FONT COLOR="#A7A9AB">
	18
</FONT>
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage194"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D228504D40F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL NARROW" ALIGN="RIGHT">
<FONT COLOR="#A7A9AB">
<B>
	FISCAL 2016
</B>
	RESULTS
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:24PT; MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	3.6.3. Canada
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2016, adjusted EBIT in the Canada segment was $345.5 million, an increase of $1.8 million compared to the same
	period last year, while the adjusted EBIT margin was stable when compared to fiscal 2015. When excluding the positive impact of a client arbitration award in Q3 2015, adjusted EBIT increased by 1.1% due to a better mix of profitable revenue, and
	growth in the financial services sector.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	3.6.4. France
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2016, adjusted EBIT in the France segment was $174.7 million, an increase of $28.1 million when compared to the same
	period last year. Adjusted EBIT margin improved to 12.1% from 11.4%. The increase in adjusted EBIT margin was mostly due to improved utilization rates on a year-over-year basis.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	3.6.5. U.K.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2016,
	adjusted EBIT in the U.K. segment was $154.3 million, a decrease of $9.3 million when compared to fiscal 2015. Adjusted EBIT margin decreased to 10.8% from 12.3% mostly due to the positive impact of additional change orders on certain large
	contracts in fiscal 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	3.6.6. ECS
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the year ended
	September&nbsp;30, 2016, adjusted EBIT was $114.3 million, a decrease of $3.9 million when compared to the same period last year. Adjusted EBIT margin was essentially stable with productivity improvements being offset by revenue impacts in the
	Netherlands as described in the revenue section.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	3.6.7. Asia Pacific
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2016, adjusted EBIT in the Asia Pacific segment was $98.6 million an increase of $21.5 million, while the margin
	improved to 18.2% from 16.2% compared to the same period last year mostly due to productivity improvements across their global delivery centers.
</P>
<EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	3.7.1. Restructuring Costs
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	In
	Q1 2016, we completed the previously announced restructuring program for productivity improvement initiatives. For the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2016, the Company incurred $29.1 million of restructuring costs for a total expense of $65.0 million
	over the entire program.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:18PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL NARROW" ALIGN="RIGHT">
<FONT COLOR="#A7A9AB">
	19
</FONT>
</P>

<A NAME="FIS_MANAGEMENTS_DISCUSSION_11"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL NARROW">
<FONT COLOR="#A7A9AB">
<B>
	MANAGEMENT&#146;S DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:24PT; MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	3.7.2. Net Finance Costs
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Net finance costs mainly include the interest on our long-term debt. The decrease in net finance costs for the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2016 was
	mainly the result of the early repayments of the May 2016 maturing tranche of the unsecured committed term loan credit facility.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	3.8. NET EARNINGS AND EARNINGS
	PER SHARE
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	3.8.1. Income Tax Expense
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For
	the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2016, the income tax expense was $384.1 million compared to $351.0 million over the same period last year, while our effective tax rate remained stable. The income tax expense was impacted by a favourable tax
	adjustment of $14.4 million in Q2 2016 attributable to the recognition of deferred tax assets following an agreement with the U.K. tax authority and an additional tax expense for an amount of $5.9 million in Q1 2016 resulting from the re-evaluation
	of our deferred tax assets following the U.K. corporate tax reduction enacted in November&nbsp;18, 2015. When excluding these tax adjustments and the tax effects from restructuring costs incurred in both years, the income tax rate would have been
	27.0% during fiscal 2016 compared to 26.3% in fiscal 2015. The increase in the income tax expense and the income tax rate was mainly attributable to the increased profitability of our U.S., India and France operations where enacted income tax rates
	are higher.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The table in section 3.8.3. shows the year-over-year comparison of the tax rate with the impact of specific items removed.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Based on the enacted rates at the end of fiscal 2016 and our current business mix, we expect our effective tax rate before any significant adjustments to
	be in the range of 27.0% to 29.0% in subsequent periods.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	3.8.2. Weighted Average Number of Shares
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For fiscal 2016, CGI&#146;s basic and diluted weighted average number of shares decreased compared to fiscal 2015 due to the impact of the repurchase of
	Class&nbsp;A subordinate voting shares, partly offset by the grants and the exercise of stock options.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:18PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL NARROW">
<FONT COLOR="#A7A9AB">
	20
</FONT>
</P>

<A NAME="FIS_MANAGEMENTS_DISCUSSION_12"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL NARROW">
<FONT COLOR="#A7A9AB">
<B>
	MANAGEMENT&#146;S DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:12PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	4. Liquidity
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:2.0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:2PT;BORDER-BOTTOM:2.00PT SOLID #000000">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
<B>
	4.1. CONSOLIDATED STATEMENTS OF CASH FLOWS
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	CGI&#146;s growth is financed through a combination of our cash flow from operations, borrowing under our existing credit facilities, the
	issuance of long-term debt, and the issuance of equity. One of our financial priorities is to maintain an optimal level of liquidity through the active management of our assets and liabilities as well as our cash flows.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	As at September&nbsp;30, 2016, cash and cash equivalents were $596.5 million. The following table provides a summary of the generation and use of cash for
	the years ended September&nbsp;30, 2016 and 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
<B>
	4.1.1. Cash Provided by Operating
	Activities
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2016, cash
	provided by operating activities was $1,333.1 million or 12.5% of revenue as compared to $1,289.3 million or 12.5% from the prior year.
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&nbsp;

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2016, $182.7 million was used to reduce our outstanding long-term debt mainly
	driven by the $129.7 million repayment under the term loan credit facility, while we made net repayments of $901.6 million to reduce our long-term debt last year. During the years ended September&nbsp;30, 2016 and 2015, the Company used $24.1
	million and $121.6 million respectively to settle the cross-currency swaps related to the outstanding long-term debt repaid during these periods.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2016, an amount of $21.8 million was used to purchase CGI Class&nbsp;A subordinate voting shares in connection with
	the Company&#146;s Performance Share Unit Plan (&#147;PSU Plan&#148;), while for the comparable period last year, an amount of $11.1 million was used. More information concerning the PSU Plan can be found in note 19 of the audited consolidated
	financial statements.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2016, we used $517.8 million to repurchase 9,319,875 Class&nbsp;A subordinate voting
	shares under the previous and current NCIB. We also used $9.5 million to pay and subsequently cancel 200,000 Class&nbsp;A subordinate voting shares repurchased and held by the Company as at the end of fiscal 2015. For the year ended
	September&nbsp;30, 2015, $323.1 million was used to repurchase 6,725,735 Class&nbsp;A subordinate voting shares under the annual aggregate limit of the NCIB then in effect.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Finally, for the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2016, we received $89.5 million in proceeds from the exercise of stock options, compared to $53.7 million
	during the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:14PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	4.1.4. Effect of Foreign Exchange Rate Changes on Cash and Cash Equivalents
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2016, the effect of foreign exchange rate changes on cash and cash equivalents was $7.2 million. This amount had no
	effect on net earnings as it was recorded in other comprehensive income.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>

<FONT COLOR="#A7A9AB">
	24
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:7PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	a
</SUP>
	Consists of Letters of Credit for $33.9 million outstanding as at
	September&nbsp;30, 2016.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Our cash position and bank lines are sufficient to support our growth strategy. At September&nbsp;30, 2016, cash and cash
	equivalents and long-term investments represented $623.8 million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Cash equivalents typically include term deposits, all with maturities of 90 days
	or less. Long-term investments include corporate and government bonds with maturities ranging from one to five years, rated &#147;A&#148; or higher.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The amount of capital available was $2,089.9 million. The long-term debt agreements contain covenants, which require us to maintain certain financial
	ratios. As at September&nbsp;30, 2016, CGI was in compliance with these covenants.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Total debt decreased by $216.1 million to $1,911.0 million as at
	September&nbsp;30, 2016, compared to $2,127.1 million as at September&nbsp;30, 2015. The variation was mainly due to the $129.7 million repayment under the unsecured committed revolving credit facility combined with other repayments.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	As at September&nbsp;30, 2016, CGI was showing a positive working capital
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	1
</SUP>
	of $425.0 million. The
	Company also had $1,466.1 million available under its unsecured committed revolving facility and is generating a significant level of cash that will allow it to fund its operations while maintaining adequate levels of liquidity. On November&nbsp;8,
	2016, the unsecured committed revolving facility was extended by two years to December 2021 and can be further extended. There were no material changes in the terms and conditions including interest rates and banking covenants.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	As at September&nbsp;30, 2016, the cash and cash equivalents held by foreign subsidiaries were $557.8 million ($263.6 million as at September&nbsp;30,
	2015). The tax implications and impact related to its repatriation will not materially affect the Company&#146;s liquidity.
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:24PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>

<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	1
</SUP>

	Working capital is defined as total current assets minus total current liabilities.
</P>

<EFX_MANAGEMENTS_DISCUSSION>
<A NAME="FIS_MANAGEMENTS_DISCUSSION_14"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL NARROW">
<FONT COLOR="#A7A9AB">
<B>
	MANAGEMENT&#146;S DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:30PT; MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	4.3. CONTRACTUAL OBLIGATIONS
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	We are committed under the terms of contractual obligations which have various expiration dates, primarily for the rental of premises, computer equipment
	used in outsourcing contracts and long-term service agreements. For the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2016, the Company decreased its commitments by $770.2 million mainly due to a decrease in rental office space commitments and repayments of
	long-term debt.
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;

<B>
	4.4. FINANCIAL INSTRUMENTS AND HEDGING TRANSACTIONS

	We use
	various financial instruments to manage our exposure to fluctuations of foreign currency exchange rates and interest rates. Please refer to notes 3 and 30 of our audited consolidated financial statements for additional information on our financial

	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="BOTTOM" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1PX SOLID #000000">
	&nbsp;
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:2PT; MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:1PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="BOTTOM" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1PX SOLID #000000" ALIGN="RIGHT">
	44
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:2PT; MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:1PT" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
</TD>
<TD NOWRAP VALIGN="BOTTOM" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1PX SOLID #000000">
	&nbsp;&nbsp;
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:2PT; MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:1PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	We use the net debt to capitalization ratio as an indication of our financial leverage in order to pursue large
	outsourcing contracts, expand global delivery centers, or make acquisitions. The net debt to capitalization ratio decreased to 15.8% in 2016 from 21.7% in 2015. The change in the net debt to capitalization ratio was mostly due to our improved cash
	generation allowing us to reduce our net debt by $446.3 million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	ROE is a measure of the return we are generating for our shareholders. ROE
	decreased to 17.2% in fiscal 2016 from 17.7% in fiscal 2015. The change was mostly the result of an increase in average capital driven by accumulated earnings.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	ROIC is a measure of the Company&#146;s efficiency in allocating the capital under our control to profitable investments. The return on invested capital
	was stable when compared to fiscal 2015 at 14.5%.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	DSO of 44 days was stable when compared to fiscal 2015. In calculating the DSO, we subtract the
	deferred revenue balance from trade accounts receivable and work in progress; for that reason, the timing of payments received from outsourcing clients in advance of the work to be performed and the timing of payments related to project milestones
	can affect the DSO fluctuations. We remain committed to manage our DSO within our 45 day target or less.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	4.6. OFF-BALANCE SHEET FINANCING AND GUARANTEES
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	CGI engages in the practice of off-balance sheet financing in the normal course of operations for a variety of transactions such as operating leases for
	office space, computer equipment and vehicles as well as accounts receivable factoring. From time to time, we also enter into agreements to provide financial or performance assurances to third parties on the sale of assets, business divestitures and
	guarantees on government and commercial contracts.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	In connection with sales of assets and business divestitures, we may be required to pay
	counterparties for costs and losses incurred as the result of breaches in our contractual obligations, representations and warranties, intellectual property right infringement and litigation against counterparties, among others. While some of the
	agreements specify a maximum potential exposure of approximately $10.8 million, others do not specify a maximum amount or limited period. It is not possible to reasonably estimate the maximum amount that may have to be paid under such guarantees.
	The amounts are dependent upon the outcome of future contingent events, the nature and likelihood of which cannot be determined at this time. The Company does not expect to incur any potential payment in connection with these guarantees that could
	have a materially adverse effect on its audited consolidated financial statements.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	In the normal course of business, we may provide certain clients,
	principally governmental entities, with bid and performance bonds. In general, we would only be liable for the amount of the bid bonds if we refuse to perform the project once the bid is awarded. We would also be liable for the performance bonds in
	the event of default in the performance of our obligations. As at September&nbsp;30, 2016, we had committed a total of $30.9 million for these bonds. To the best of our knowledge, we complied with our performance obligations under all service
	contracts for which there was a performance or bid bond, and the ultimate liability, if any, incurred in connection with these guarantees would not have a materially adverse effect on our consolidated results of operations or financial condition.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:18PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL NARROW" ALIGN="RIGHT">
<FONT COLOR="#A7A9AB">
	27
</FONT>
</P>

<EFX_MANAGEMENTS_DISCUSSION>
<A NAME="FIS_MANAGEMENTS_DISCUSSION_15"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL NARROW">
<FONT COLOR="#A7A9AB">
<B>
	MANAGEMENT&#146;S DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:30PT; MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	4.7. CAPABILITY TO DELIVER RESULTS
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Sufficient capital resources and liquidity are required for supporting ongoing business operations and to execute our build and buy growth strategy. The
	Company has sufficient capital resources coming from the cash generated from operations, credit facilities, long-term debt agreements and invested capital from shareholders. Our principal uses of cash are for procuring new large outsourcing and
	managed services contracts; investing in our business solutions; pursuing accretive acquisitions; buying back CGI shares and paying down debt. Funds are also used to expand our global delivery network as more and more of our clients demand lower
	cost alternatives. In terms of financing, we are well positioned to continue executing our four-pillar growth strategy in fiscal 2017.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Strong and
	experienced leadership is essential to successfully implement our Company&#146;s strategy. CGI has a strong leadership team with members who are highly knowledgeable and have gained a significant amount of experience within the IT industry via
	various career paths and leadership roles. CGI fosters leadership development to ensure a continuous flow of knowledge and strength is maintained throughout the organization. As part of our succession planning in key positions, we established the
	Leadership Institute, our own corporate university, to develop leadership, technical and managerial skills inspired by CGI&#146;s roots and traditions.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	As a Company built on human capital, our professionals and their knowledge are critical to delivering quality service to our clients. Our human resources
	program provides competitive compensation and benefits, a favourable working environment, and our training and career development programs combine to allow us to attract and retain the best talent. Employee satisfaction is monitored regularly
	through a Company-wide survey. Furthermore, approximately 52,000 of our members, are also owners of CGI through our Share Purchase Plan. The Share Purchase Plan, along with the Profit Participation Program, allows members to share in the success of
	the Company and aligns member objectives with our strategic goals.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	In addition to our capital resources and the talent of our human capital, CGI has
	established a Management Foundation encompassing governance policies, sophisticated management frameworks and an organizational model for its business units and corporate processes. This foundation, along with our appropriate internal systems, helps
	in providing a disciplined high standard of quality service to our clients across all of our operations, and additional value to our stakeholders. CGI&#146;s operations maintain appropriate certifications in accordance with service requirements such
	as the ISO and CMMI certification programs.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:18PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL NARROW">
<FONT COLOR="#A7A9AB">
	28
</FONT>
</P>

	5.1. FOREIGN EXCHANGE
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The Company operates globally and is
	exposed to changes in foreign currency rates. Accordingly, as prescribed by IFRS, we value assets, liabilities and transactions that are measured in foreign currencies using various exchange rates. We report all dollar amounts in Canadian dollars.
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL NARROW">
<FONT COLOR="#A7A9AB">
<B>
	MANAGEMENT&#146;S DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:24PT; MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	5.2. REVENUE VARIATION AND REVENUE BY SEGMENT
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The following table provides a summary of the year-over-year changes in our revenue, in total and by segment, separately showing the impacts of foreign
	currency exchange rate variations between the Q4 2016 and Q4 2015 periods. The Q4 2015 revenue by segment was recorded reflecting the actual average foreign exchange rates for that period. The foreign exchange impact is the difference between the
	current period&#146;s actual results and the current period&#146;s results converted with the prior year&#146;s average foreign exchange rates.
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	We ended the fourth quarter of fiscal 2016 with revenue of $2,582.4 million, essentially stable when compared to
	the same period of fiscal 2015. On a constant currency basis, revenue increased by $71.8 million or 2.8%. Foreign currency rate fluctuations unfavourably impacted our revenue by $74.7 million or 2.9%.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:18PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL NARROW">
<FONT COLOR="#A7A9AB">
	30
</FONT>
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage206"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D228504D40F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL NARROW" ALIGN="RIGHT">
<FONT COLOR="#A7A9AB">
<B>
	FISCAL 2016
</B>
	RESULTS
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:24PT; MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	5.2.1. U.S.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Revenue in our U.S. segment was $721.5 million in Q4 2016, a decrease of $30.7 million or 4.1% compared to the same period of fiscal 2015. On a constant
	currency basis, revenue decreased by $26.6 million or 3.5%. The change in revenue was mostly due to the non-renewal of contracts in the U.S. government market, mainly in the defense sector, partly offset by an increased volume of work within the
	U.S. federal civilian agencies.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the current quarter, the top two U.S. vertical markets were government and financial services, which together
	accounted for approximately 77% of its revenue.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:14PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	5.2.2. Nordics
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Revenue from our Nordics segment was $358.6 million in Q4 2016, a decrease of $9.5 million or 2.6% compared to the same period of fiscal 2015. On a
	constant currency basis, revenue decreased by $7.0 million or 1.9%. The change in revenue is mainly due to the expiration of certain infrastructure outsourcing contracts and an increased usage of our offshore delivery centers in Asia Pacific. This
	was partly offset by an increased work volume within the MRD vertical market for both Sweden and Denmark.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the current quarter, the Nordics&#146;
	top two vertical markets were MRD and government, which together accounted for approximately 65% of its revenue.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:14PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	5.2.3. Canada
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Revenue in our Canada segment for Q4 2016 was $387.0 million, an increase of $15.2 million or 4.1% compared to the same period of fiscal 2015. The
	increase of revenue was mostly due to an increase in financial services, including IP-based services and solutions revenue, as well as new outsourcing contracts within the MRD vertical market. This was partly offset by the expiration of certain
	infrastructure outsourcing contracts.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the current quarter, Canada&#146;s top two vertical markets were financial services and
	telecommunications&nbsp;&amp; utilities, which together accounted for approximately 60% of its revenue.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:14PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	5.2.4. France
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Revenue from our France segment was $341.7 million in Q4 2016 an increase of $27.4 million or 8.7% compared to the same period of fiscal 2015. On a
	constant currency basis, revenue increased by $27.9 million or 8.9%. The increase in revenue was mostly due to an increase in work volume across the majority of its vertical markets and, to a lesser extent, a recent business acquisition.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the current quarter, France&#146;s top two vertical markets were MRD and financial services, which together accounted for approximately 63% of its
	revenue.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:14PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	5.2.5. U.K.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Revenue from our U.K. segment was
	$343.1 million in Q4 2016, a decrease of $12.0 million or 3.4% compared to the same period of fiscal 2015. On a constant currency basis, revenue increased by $51.1 million or 14.4%. The increase in revenue was mainly due to new outsourcing contracts
	in the government market combined with higher work volume in telecommunications&nbsp;&amp; utilities. In addition, revenue in Q4 2016 was favourably impacted by the sale of additional equipment. The growth was partly offset by lower work volume with
	a client in the MRD vertical market.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the current quarter, U.K.&#146;s top two vertical markets were government and telecommunications&nbsp;&amp;
	utilities, which together accounted for approximately 73% of its revenue.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:18PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL NARROW" ALIGN="RIGHT">
<FONT COLOR="#A7A9AB">
	31
</FONT>
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage207"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D228504D40F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
</EFX_MANAGEMENTS_DISCUSSION>
<EFX_MANAGEMENTS_DISCUSSION>
<A NAME="FIS_MANAGEMENTS_DISCUSSION_17"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL NARROW">
<FONT COLOR="#A7A9AB">
<B>
	MANAGEMENT&#146;S DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:36PT; MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	5.2.6. ECS
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Revenue from our ECS segment was $288.4 million in Q4 2016, a decrease of $7.3 million or 2.5% when compared to fiscal 2015. The change in revenue was
	mostly due to lower work volume and projects completed in the Netherlands, lower work volume combined with the divesting of certain low margin contracts in Southern Europe and the wind-down of the majority of our operations in South America. This
	was partly offset by an increased work volume in Germany mainly in MRD and telecommunications&nbsp;&amp; utilities vertical markets.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the current
	quarter, ECS&#146; top two vertical markets were MRD and telecommunications&nbsp;&amp; utilities, which together accounted for approximately 64% of its revenue.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	5.2.7. Asia Pacific
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Revenue from our Asia Pacific segment was
	$142.2 million in Q4 2016, an increase of $14.1 million or 11.0% compared to the same period of fiscal 2015. On a constant currency basis, revenue increased by $18.2 million or 14.2%. The increase in revenue was due to the continued increased demand
	of our offshore delivery centers across our segments, as our clients continue taking advantage of our global delivery network. This was partly offset by lower work volumes in Australia.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the current quarter, Asia Pacific&#146;s top two vertical markets were telecommunications&nbsp;&amp; utilities and MRD, which together accounted for
	approximately 69% of its revenue.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:18PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL NARROW">
<FONT COLOR="#A7A9AB">
	32
</FONT>
</P>

<B>
	&nbsp;
</B>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="BOTTOM" BGCOLOR="#A9A9A9" ALIGN="RIGHT">
<B>
	4.3
</B>
</TD>
<TD NOWRAP VALIGN="BOTTOM" BGCOLOR="#A9A9A9">

	%&nbsp;

<TR STYLE="FONT-SIZE:1PT" BGCOLOR="#A9A9A9">

<TR BGCOLOR="#A9A9A9" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL; FONT-SIZE:8PT">

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:2.00EM; TEXT-INDENT:-1.00EM; FONT-SIZE:8PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
<I>
	Adjusted EBIT margin
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:1PT; MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:1PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="BOTTOM" BGCOLOR="#A9A9A9" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1PX SOLID #000000">
	&nbsp;&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="BOTTOM" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1PX SOLID #000000" BGCOLOR="#A9A9A9">

<I>
	&nbsp;
</I>
</B>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:1PT; MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:1PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="BOTTOM" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1PX SOLID #000000" BGCOLOR="#A9A9A9" ALIGN="RIGHT">
<B>
<I>
	15.3%
</I>
</B>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:1PT; MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:1PT" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
</TD>
<TD NOWRAP VALIGN="BOTTOM" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1PX SOLID #000000" BGCOLOR="#A9A9A9">

</I>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:1PT; MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:1PT" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&nbsp;
</P>

<TD NOWRAP VALIGN="BOTTOM" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1PX SOLID #000000" BGCOLOR="#A9A9A9">

</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Adjusted EBIT for the quarter was $395.1 million an increase of $16.1 million or 4.3% from Q4 2015, while the
	margin improved to 15.3% from 14.7%.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	5.3.1. U.S.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Adjusted
	EBIT in the U.S. segment was $128.5 million for Q4 2016, an increase of $11.2 million year-over-year. Adjusted EBIT margin increased to 17.8% from 15.6% when compared to Q4 2015 mostly due to additional research and development tax credits and the
	decrease in amortization of client relationships related to the acquisition of Stanley, Inc.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	5.3.2. Nordics
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Adjusted EBIT in the Nordics segment was $43.8 million for Q4 2016, an increase of $13.6 million year-over-year, while adjusted EBIT margin increased to
	12.2% from 8.2% in Q4 2015. The increase in adjusted EBIT margin came mainly from the ongoing cost synergies within our infrastructure business and the savings generated from the restructuring program.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	5.3.3. Canada
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Adjusted EBIT in the Canada segment was $94.1
	million for Q4 2016, an increase of $16.7 million year-over-year while adjusted EBIT margin increased to 24.3% from 20.8%. This increase was mostly the result of an improved mix of IP-based services and solutions revenue related to license sales.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	5.3.4. France
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Adjusted EBIT in the France segment was
	$43.1 million for Q4 2016, an increase of $7.3 million year-over-year. Adjusted EBIT margin improved to 12.6% from 11.4%. The increase in adjusted EBIT margin was mostly due to improved utilization rates on a year-over-year basis.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:18PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL NARROW" ALIGN="RIGHT">
<FONT COLOR="#A7A9AB">
	33
</FONT>
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage209"></A>

</EFX_MANAGEMENTS_DISCUSSION>
<EFX_MANAGEMENTS_DISCUSSION>
<A NAME="FIS_MANAGEMENTS_DISCUSSION_18"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL NARROW">
<FONT COLOR="#A7A9AB">
<B>
	MANAGEMENT&#146;S DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:36PT; MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:2PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:24PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	5.3.5. U.K.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Adjusted EBIT in the U.K. segment was $28.7 million for Q4 2016, a decrease of $33.7 million year-over-year. Adjusted EBIT margin decreased to 8.4% from
	17.6% due mostly to the positive impact of additional change orders on certain large contracts in Q4 2015 and a provision taken on a client contract in Q4 2016.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	5.3.6. ECS
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Adjusted EBIT in the ECS segment was $30.3 million
	for Q4 2016, a decrease of $6.6 million year-over-year, while the margin was 10.5% compared to 12.5% in Q4 2015. The change in margin was mostly due to the revenue impacts from the Netherlands described in the revenue section.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	5.3.7. Asia Pacific
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Adjusted EBIT in the Asia Pacific segment
	was $26.6 million for Q4 2016, an increase of $7.7 million year-over-year, while the margin increased to 18.7% from 14.8%. This was mainly due to productivity improvements across their global delivery centers. In addition, during Q4 2015, adjusted
	EBIT margin was unfavourably impacted by of a provision on a contract in the Middle East.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:18PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL NARROW">
<FONT COLOR="#A7A9AB">
	34
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For the current quarter, the increase in earnings before income taxes mainly came from the increase in adjusted EBIT
	as described in section 5.3 of the present document. In addition, $35.9 million of restructuring costs were incurred in Q4 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	In Q4 2016, the
	income tax expense was $103.0 million, an increase of $16.8 million compared to $86.2 million in Q4 2015, while our effective income tax rate increased from 27.0% to 27.3%. The increase in income tax rate was mainly attributable to the decrease in
	U.K earnings where the enacted tax rate is lower.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Net earnings were $274.4 million, an increase of $41.5 million compared to $232.9 million last
	year.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The table in section 5.4.1 shows the quarterly year-over-year comparison of the tax rate with the impact of restructuring costs removed.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	During the quarter, no Class&nbsp;A subordinate voting shares were repurchased while 924,816 stock options were exercised.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:18PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL NARROW" ALIGN="RIGHT">
<FONT COLOR="#A7A9AB">
	35
</FONT>
</P>

	$451.3 million in Q4 2015, or 15.6% of revenue compared to 17.5% last year.

	$12.9 million of net change in non-cash working capital items was mostly due to:

	&nbsp;

	mainly driven by the reduction in vacation accruals, the timing of payments of sales and payroll taxes, and payroll accruals.
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:24PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	5.5.2. Cash Used in
	Investing Activities
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For Q4 2016,$101.3&nbsp;million were used in investing activities while $79.3 million were used in the prior year.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The following table provides a summary of the generation and use of cash from investing activities:

<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;

	The purchase of property, plant and equipment due to investments across our data center infrastructure operations and
	global delivery centers; and,

<TR STYLE="FONT-SIZE:1PT" BGCOLOR="#A9A9A9">
<TD HEIGHT="5" BGCOLOR="#A9A9A9">
</TD>
<TD HEIGHT="5" COLSPAN="2" BGCOLOR="#A9A9A9">
</TD>
<TD HEIGHT="5" COLSPAN="2" BGCOLOR="#A9A9A9">
</TD>
<TD HEIGHT="5" COLSPAN="2" BGCOLOR="#A9A9A9">
</TD>
</TR>
<TR BGCOLOR="#A9A9A9" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
<TD VALIGN="TOP" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1PX SOLID #000000" BGCOLOR="#A9A9A9">
<P STYLE=" MARGIN-TOP:0PT ; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:1.00EM; TEXT-INDENT:-1.00EM; FONT-SIZE:8PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	&nbsp;Cash used in financing
	activities
</B>
</P>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="BOTTOM" BGCOLOR="#A9A9A9" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1PX SOLID #000000">
	&nbsp;&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="BOTTOM" ALIGN="RIGHT" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1PX SOLID #000000" BGCOLOR="#A9A9A9">
<B>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;(1,473)&nbsp;
</B>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="BOTTOM" BGCOLOR="#A9A9A9" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1PX SOLID #000000">
	&nbsp;&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="BOTTOM" ALIGN="RIGHT" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1PX SOLID #000000" BGCOLOR="#A9A9A9">
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;(366,092)&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="BOTTOM" BGCOLOR="#A9A9A9" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1PX SOLID #000000">
	&nbsp;&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="BOTTOM" ALIGN="RIGHT" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1PX SOLID #000000" BGCOLOR="#A9A9A9">
<B>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;364,619&nbsp;&nbsp;
</B>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</DIV>
</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	During Q4 2016, $16.7 million was used to reduce our outstanding long-term debt while for the same period last year
	$120.8 million was used mainly driven by $121.9 million in repayments under the term loan credit facility.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	During Q4 2016, we did not repurchase
	Class&nbsp;A subordinate voting shares under the NCIB. For the same period last year, we used $229.0 million to repurchase 4,850,402 Class&nbsp;A subordinate voting shares under the NCIB.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	In Q4 2016, we received $15.2 million in proceeds from the exercise of stock options, compared to $7.0 million during the same period last year.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:18PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL NARROW">
<FONT COLOR="#A7A9AB">
	38
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	There are factors causing quarterly variances which may not be reflective of the Company&#146;s future performance.
	First, there is seasonality in systems integration and consulting work, and the quarterly performance of these operations is impacted by occurrences such as vacations and the number of statutory holidays in any given quarter. Outsourcing contracts
	including BPS contracts are affected to a lesser extent by seasonality. Second, the workflow from some clients may fluctuate from quarter to quarter based on their business cycle and the seasonality of their own operations. Third, the savings that
	we generate for a client on a given outsourcing contract may temporarily reduce our revenue stream from this client, as these savings may not be immediately offset by additional work performed for this client.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	In general, cash flow from operating activities could vary significantly from quarter to quarter depending on the timing of monthly payments received from
	large clients, cash requirements associated with large acquisitions, outsourcing contracts
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:18PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL NARROW" ALIGN="RIGHT">
<FONT COLOR="#A7A9AB">
	39
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL NARROW">
<FONT COLOR="#A7A9AB">
<B>
	MANAGEMENT&#146;S DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:24PT; MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:2PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:24PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	and
	projects, the timing of the reimbursements for various tax credits as well as profit sharing payments to members and the timing of restructuring cost payments.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Foreign exchange fluctuations can also contribute to quarterly variances as our percentage of operations in foreign countries evolves. The effect from
	these variances is primarily on our revenue and to a much lesser extent, on our margin as we benefit from natural hedges.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;

<FONT COLOR="#A7A9AB">
	40
</FONT>

<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY" STYLE=" MARGIN-TOP:0PT ; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL; FONT-SIZE:12PT">
<B>
	Changes in Accounting Policies
</B>
</P>
</TD>

<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;

	&nbsp;

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The audited consolidated financial statements for the year ended September&nbsp;30, 2016 include all adjustments that CGI&#146;s management considers
	necessary for the fair presentation of its financial position, results of operations, and cash flows.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	FUTURE ACCOUNTING STANDARD CHANGES
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The following standards have been issued but are not yet effective:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	IFRS 15 - Revenue from Contracts with Customers
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	In May 2014,
	the IASB issued IFRS 15, &#147;Revenue from Contracts with Customers&#148;, to specify how and when to recognize revenue as well as requiring the provision of more informative and relevant disclosures. The standard supersedes IAS 18,
	&#147;Revenue&#148;, IAS 11, &#147;Construction Contracts&#148;, and other revenue related Interpretations. The standard will be effective on October&nbsp;1, 2018 for the Company, with earlier adoption permitted. The Company is currently evaluating
	the impact of this standard on its consolidated financial statements.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	IFRS 9 - Financial Instruments
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	In July 2014, the IASB amended IFRS 9, &#147;Financial Instruments&#148;, to bring together the classification and measurement, impairment and hedge
	accounting phases of the IASB&#146;s project to replace IAS 39, &#147;Financial Instruments: Recognition and Measurement&#148;. The standard supersedes all previous versions of IFRS 9 and will be effective on October&nbsp;1, 2018 for the Company,
	with earlier adoption permitted. The Company is currently evaluating the impact of this standard on its consolidated financial statements.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL">
<B>
	IFRS 16 - Leases
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	In January 2016, the IASB issued IFRS 16, &#147;Leases&#148;, to set out the principles for the recognition, measurement, presentation and
	disclosure of leases for both parties to a lease contract. The standard supersedes IAS 17, &#147;Leases&#148;, and other lease related Interpretations. The standard will be effective on October&nbsp;1, 2019 for the Company with earlier adoption
	permitted only if IFRS 15 &#147;Revenue from Contracts with Customers&#148; is also applied. The Company is currently evaluating the impact of this standard on its consolidated financial statements.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:18PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL NARROW" ALIGN="RIGHT">
<FONT COLOR="#A7A9AB">
	41
</FONT>
</P>

<B>
	MANAGEMENT&#146;S DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS
</B>

<B>
	8.
</B>
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY" STYLE=" MARGIN-TOP:0PT ; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL; FONT-SIZE:12PT">
<B>
	Critical Accounting Estimates
</B>
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:2.0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:2PT;BORDER-BOTTOM:2.00PT SOLID #000000">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The Company&#146;s significant accounting policies are described in note 3 of the audited consolidated financial statements for the year ended September
	30, 2016. Certain of these accounting policies, listed below, require management to make accounting estimates and judgment that affect the reported amounts of assets, liabilities and equity and the accompanying disclosures at the date of the
	consolidated financial statements as well as the reported amounts of revenue and expenses during the reporting period. These accounting estimates are considered critical because they require management to make subjective and/or complex judgments
	that are inherently uncertain and because they could have a material impact on the presentation of our financial condition, changes in financial condition or results of operations.
</P>
